doc.title: 3Q25 EPS REVIEW Consistent results driven by NIM expansion and benign credit
doc.source_uri: 2025-08-28/Canadian Imperial Bank of Commerce 3Q25 EPS REVIEW Consistent results driven by NIM expansion and benign creditCanadian _2025-08-28

passages.text: Results again exceeded consensus, driven by better-than- expected fee income and NII, and lower PCL, partially offset by higher than expected expenses. Credit quality showed modest normalization with GILs lower but GIL formations up. Its outlook continues to call for impaired PCLs in the mid-30bps.

Bottom line: Results in 3Q25 again exceeded expectations, driven by better than expected fee income and NII and lower than anticipated PCL, partially offset by higher than expected expenses. Credit quality showed modest normalization with GILs down but GIL formations up. Capital remains healthy with its CET1 ratio relatively stable at \(13.4\%\) even as it completes its share repurchase program. Looking out, it continues to see impaired PCLs in the mid- 30bps range, while NIM in both Canada and the US are expected to move gradually higher based on the forward curve. It continues to see loan growth in the low- to- mid single- digit range.

Results: CM reported 3Q25 EPS of C\\$2.15. Excluding C\\$11mn amortization of acquisition- related intangibles, EPS was C\\$2.16. Consensus was C\\$2.00. The beat was driven by a higher- than- expected fee income and NII and a lower- than- modeled PCL, partially offset by higher expenses. Total revenue increased \(10\%\) y- o- y and \(3\%\) sequentially. Book value increased \(0.1\%\) to C\\$60.18 (1.7x). Its CET1 ratio was unchanged at \(13.4\%\) . It generated an adjusted ROE of \(14.2\%\) \((+30\) bps from 2Q25). Average diluted shares decreased \(0.6\%\) .

Drivers: Relative to 2Q25, results evidenced higher NII on continued NIM expansion (+4bps) and a modestly larger balance sheet, lower fee income but higher expenses, a lower PCL, a stable tax rate and a lower average share count.

Estimates: Following 3Q25 results we are raising our 2025 EPS estimate to C\\$8.45 (+C\\$0.25) and our 2026 EPS to C\\$8.85 (+C\\$0.55) on continued growth in NII and benign credit trends. Our price target is C\\$106 (+C\\$10) and is based on 12x our 2026 EPS estimate of C\\$8.85 (was 11.5x our prior 2026 EPS estimate).

**Why UNDERWEIGHT?**
While NIM headwinds have abated, expense growth and credit normalization continue to weigh on return improvement.
**Upside case** CAD 117.00
If NIM pressure abates and economic growth rebounds, we see a higher EPS of C\(9.35 with modest multiple expansion to 12.5x multiple leading to a C\)11T upside case.
**Downside case** CAD 95.00
If credit costs increase at a faster pace in an economic recession, we could see 2026E EPS declining to C\(8.25 and multiple compression to 11.5x leading to a C\)87 downside case.
**Upside/Downside scenarios**
Amortization of acquisition- related intangibles was C\$11mn (\\$0.01).
NIM: CM expects margins in both Canada and the US to move gradually higher based on the forward curve.
Loan growth: CM noted that loan pipelines are solid and it expects to meet its previous guidance for low- to- mid single- digit loan growth for the year.
Interest Rate Sensitivity: CM estimates a C\$147mn benefit to NII from a +100bps shift in rates and a C\$225mn decrease in NII from a - 100bps shift.
Credit: CM reiterated its guidance for a full year impaired loss rate in the mid- 30bps (33bps at 3Q25).
Corporate Segment: CM continues to project a quarterly loss between C\$0 and C\$50mn for the corporate segment (C\$108mn loss in 3Q25 due to write downs).

Capital: CM aims to maintain a 75- 100bps buffer above capital regulatory minimums, which results in a CET1 ratio in the - 12.5% range currently. It repurchased 5.5mn shares in 3Q25 and has announced an intention to launch another normal course issuer bid for 2% of the outstanding common shares.

NII higher: Reported net interest income increased 6.9% from 2Q25. Excluding the impact of trading, NII rose 7.2%. Its NIM increased 4bps to 1.58%. Ex. trading, NIM rose 6bp to 1.94%. Average earning assets increased slightly.
Loans grow. Period- end loans grew 1.8% q- o- q, led by business & government (+3.0%) followed by credit card (+2.6%), residential mortgages (+0.9%) and personal (+0.9%).
Deposits higher. Deposit balances increased 1.0% to C\$793bn. Its deposit mix was 87% interest- bearing demand deposits and 13% non- interest bearing.

Fees lower: Non- interest income decreased 0.9% sequentially due to lower trading and lower gains from debt securities partially offset by higher underwriting and advisory fees and higher fee based revenue.

Costs higher. Adjusted expenses increased 4.1% sequentially due to higher performance- based compensation and employee- related compensation and higher computer, software and office equipment expenses.

GILs down slightly. Gross impaired loans decreased slightly to C\$3.281bn, primarily due to a decrease in business and government loans partially offset by an increase in consumer loans. Its GIL ratio declined 1bp to 0.56%. GIL formations were C\$1.320bn up 7.8% from 2Q25.
PCL lower. Its PCL was C\$559mn, down 7.6% from 2Q25. Net write- offs were C\$401mn, up from C\$393mn in the prior quarter. Its ACL coverage ratio rose 1bp to 78bps.

Line of Business ResultsIts 3Q25 revenue mix was 43% Canadian Personal & Business Banking, 24% Canadian Commercial Banking & Wealth Management, 8% US Commercial Banking & Wealth Management, 21% Capital Markets & Direct Financial Services and 2% Corporate & Other.

Canadian Personal & Business BankingRevenues of C\$3.061bn rose 10% y- o- y and 7% q- o- q. NII was up 13% y- o- y driven primarily by strong margins. Expenses increased 3% y- o- y due to higher employee- related costs and spending on technology and growth. PCLs increased C\$102mm y- o- y. Net income of C\$812mn was 17% higher compared to 3Q24. ROE was 25.9% compared to 24.2% in 2Q25 and 22.7% in 3Q24. Average loan balances increased 2% and average deposit balances increased 0.1% y- o- y.

Canadian Commercial Banking & Wealth ManagementRevenue was C\$1.723bn, up 13% y- o- y with NII up 28% (+18% ex. impact of benchmark reform) and fee income grew 4% (+10% ex impact of benchmark reform on higher asset balances resulting from market appreciation and net sales). Expenses were up 11% compared to 3Q24 due to higher performance- based compensation and spending on technology and growth. Net income was C\$598mn, increased 19% y- o- y and 9% q- o- q. The segment's ROE was 23.8% compared to 23% in 2Q25 and 20.8% in 3Q24. Assets under management were C\$295bn, an increase of 10% compared to 3Q24 and 7% compared to 2Q25. Assets under administration were C\$552bn, up 12% compared to 3Q24 and fell 7% compared to 2Q25.

US Commercial Banking & Wealth ManagementRevenue was US\$576mn, up 8% y- o- y with NII up 14%, driven by deposit volumes and margin expansion. Fee income down 4% y- o- y. Adjusted expenses were up 8% compared to 3Q24 mainly due to ongoing investments in people and infrastructure and performance- based compensation. PCLs decreased US\$19mm y- o- y and US\$72mm q- o- q to US\$14mn. Net income was US\$186mn an increase of 52% q- o- q. It generated an ROE of 9% compared to 7.8% in 3Q24 and 6% in 2Q25. Assets under management were US\$88bn, an increase of 6% compared to 3Q24 and 7% compared to 2Q25. Assets under administration were \$108bn, up 1% compared to 3Q24 and 6% compared to 2Q25.

Capital Markets & Direct Financial ServicesRevenue of C\$1.506bn was up 38% y- o- y (+24% adjusted). Global markets adjusted revenue increased 18% y- o- y (+40% reported) with growth across most products, while corporate & investment banking rose 34% on higher underwriting and advisory activities, as well growth in lending. PCLs increased C\$35mm y- o- y and C\$42mm q- o- q. Expenses increased 11% y- o- y, driven by higher performance- based compensation and investments in technology and growth. Net income was C\$540mn, an increase of 87% y- o- y (+43% adjusted) and down 5% q- o- q. The segment produced an ROE of 20.7% compared to 22.9% in 2Q25 and 12.3% in 3Q24.
Corporate & OtherReported a net loss of C\$108mm compared to a net loss of C\$15mm in the prior quarter.
